story.notes: I have not found a death certificate or grave for Sarah R, his first wife, but there is a 1762 marriage certificate for Phillips S and Mary P; the second marriage is reflected in the Sweetser Genealogy; and the Leominster Vital Records (LVR) show William Pitt S as the child of Samuel and Mary.  William Pitt was born in 1763, before Samuel.  However, the LVR shows Samuel as the child of Phillips and Sarah.  Furthermore, the Richardson family genealogy shows Samuel as the son of Sarah (although this could have been be pulled from the LVR);  I have wondered whether the marriage of Phillips and Mary and the birth of William Pitt (and later John and Mary) involved Phillips, Sr., who might have taken a younger wife when his wife (also Mary) died, but there is no evidence of this (and in fact no documentation of the death of Phillips, Sr. or his wife).  At any rate, Phillips, Jr. came to Leominster in 1743, then to Winchendon; served as a Sergeant in the 4/19/1775 Cambridge alarm and then as a Private in 1776 – 1778; his son Phillips III (1760) moved to Marlborough, NH around 1799 (and ran the Sweetser Tavern there, photo in file) and Phillips, Jr. (1731) appears to have moved with him

story.notes: Using FamilySearch Full Text search, I was able to uncover what I think is the history of Phillips’ second wife; she was married (1) 6/2/1743 to Captain John Stebbins (died 1756 at Fort Edwards in French and Indian War) (his second wife, at least 2 children by the first) of Leicester, MA; he was 35 years older than her; I believe they had at least 2 and likely 3 children; she married (2) Nathaniel Parmenter (born 1729, so 8 years younger than her)  of Spencer, MA, his second wife; he had 2 children by his first marriage and 1 child (Nathan Parmenter) with Mary; Nathaniel enlisted in 1759 to serve in the French and Indian War and was soon killed/died near Lake Champlain; a story in town was that he had enlisted after a dispute with his wife, but the enlistment bounty may have been the real reason; his sons by his first marriage were placed with his brothers after his death and Mary took Nathaniel to her third marriage, to Phillips Sweetser; I speculate she had a daughter Patience (b. 1747) with Stebbins who stayed with her into her marriage with Sweetser as Patience’s grandson, William Heywood, had the middle name “Sweetser”; he was the author of the Westminster history (1893) where Mary’s marital history is recounted; and buyer beware:  this is my best estimate of the history, but parts still seem strange, such as her age (44) when Samuel was born in 1765 – unusual, but not unheard of

Almy Morris to Richard Morris to Job Morris to Lydia Morris Ansley to Ann Ansley Carter to Littleberry Walker Carter to Wm Archibald Carter to Earl Carter to Jimmy); ancestor to Richard Nixon (Thomas, Sr. to Eliz. Cornell Almy to Eliz. Almy Morris to Richard Morris to Sarah Morris Burdg to Jacob Burdg, Sr. to Jacob Burdg., Jr. to Oliver Burdg to Almira Burdg Milhous to Hannah Milhous Nixon to Richard Milhous Nixon); also an ancestor to Bill Gates (through his mother)
